`grainsize` specifies the smallest unit of work that will be processed by a thread in parallel execution. A smaller `grainsize` means that the workload is divided into smaller chunks, which can lead to better load balancing across threads. However, it also incurs overhead because of the increased number of task management operations. Conversely, a large `grainsize` reduces the overhead but may lead to uneven workload distribution and underutilization of CPU cores, especially if some tasks complete significantly faster than others.

