To implement parallel reduction for operations such as sum, min, or max using `parallel_reduce` with oneTBB, you can define a custom reduction body by creating a class that encapsulates the reduction logic. Here are examples showing how to achieve this for both summation and finding the minimum element in an array.

### 1. Implementing Parallel Sum

For summation, you can create a class called `SumFoo`. This class will hold the state during computation and will define the reduction logic in the `operator()` method.

```cpp
#include <oneapi/tbb/parallel_reduce.h>
#include <cmath> // for FLT_MAX

class SumFoo {
    float* my_a; // Pointer to the input array
public:
    float my_sum; // Result of the reduction

    void operator()(const tbb::blocked_range<size_t>& r) {
        float sum = my_sum; // Initialize sum with current value
        for (size_t i = r.begin(); i != r.end(); ++i) {
            sum += Foo(my_a[i]); // Apply Foo function and accumulate
        }
        my_sum = sum; // Store result back
    }

    SumFoo(SumFoo& x, tbb::split) : my_a(x.my_a), my_sum(0) {} // Split constructor

    void join(const SumFoo& y) {
        my_sum += y.my_sum; // Combine results from different threads
    }

    SumFoo(float a[]) : my_a(a), my_sum(0) {} // Constructor
};

// Function to execute parallel summation
float ParallelSumFoo(const float a[], size_t n) {
    SumFoo sf(a); // Create a reduction object
    tbb::parallel_reduce(tbb::blocked_range<size_t>(0, n), sf); // Perform the reduction
    return sf.my_sum; // Return the final result
}
```

### 2. Implementing Parallel Minimum

For finding the minimum, you can use a similar structure with a different logic for accumulation.

```cpp
#include <oneapi/tbb/parallel_reduce.h>
#include <cfloat> // for FLT_MAX

class MinIndexFoo {
    const float* const my_a; // Pointer to the input array
public:
    float value_of_min; // Minimum value found
    long index_of_min; // Index of the minimum value

    void operator()(const tbb::blocked_range<size_t>& r) {
        const float* a = my_a;
        for (size_t i = r.begin(); i != r.end(); ++i) {
            float value = Foo(a[i]); // Apply Foo to get value
            if (value < value_of_min) { // Check for new minimum
                value_of_min = value;
                index_of_min = i; // Update index
            }
        }
    }

    MinIndexFoo(MinIndexFoo& x, tbb::split) :
        my_a(x.my_a),
        value_of_min(FLT_MAX), // Initialize to maximum value
        index_of_min(-1) {}     // Invalid initial index

    void join(const MinIndexFoo& y) {
        if (y.value_of_min < value_of_min) { // Compare and update
            value_of_min = y.value_of_min;
            index_of_min = y.index_of_min;
        }
    }

    MinIndexFoo(const float a[]) :
        my_a(a),
        value_of_min(FLT_MAX),
        index_of_min(-1) {} // Constructor
};

// Function to execute parallel minimum search
long ParallelMinIndexFoo(float a[], size_t n) {
    MinIndexFoo mif(a); // Create a reduction object
    tbb::parallel_reduce(tbb::blocked_range<size_t>(0, n), mif); // Perform the reduction
    return mif.index_of_min; // Return index of the minimum
}
```

### Conclusion

In summary, the `parallel_reduce` function effectively allows you to perform reductions in parallel by defining a class for your reduction logic. By properly implementing the `operator()`, constructors for splitting, and a `join` function, you can handle custom operations such as sum and min in an efficient manner. Make sure to include the necessary headers as shown in the examples.

