When migrating from legacy TBB (2020) to oneTBB, several breaking changes must be considered. Here are the key points:

### 1. Interface Incompatibilities

If your application uses Parallel STL algorithms with `libstdc++` versions 9 or 10, you may encounter compilation failures due to changes in interfaces between TBB and oneTBB. To resolve this, disable Parallel STL support in your project using the following definitions:

```cpp
#define PSTL_USE_PARALLEL_POLICIES 0 // For libstdc++ 9
// or
#define _GLIBCXX_USE_TBB_PAR_BACKEND 0 // For libstdc++ 10

#include <first_standard_header.h>
#include <parallel_stl_algorithm.h>
```

### 2. Task API Changes

The way you dynamically add work has changed significantly. In legacy TBB, you would use `tbb::parallel_do`, but in oneTBB, you should use `oneapi::tbb::parallel_for_each`. Here’s how to modify your code:

**Legacy TBB Example:**

```cpp
#include <cstddef>
#include <vector>
#include <tbb/task.h>

struct Task : public tbb::task {
    // Custom task implementation
};
```

**Migrated to oneTBB:**

```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <oneapi/tbb/parallel_for_each.h>

int main() {
    std::vector<int> items = {0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7};

    oneapi::tbb::parallel_for_each(
        items.begin(), items.end(),
        [](int& i, tbb::feeder<int>& feeder) {
            // add more work here if needed
        }
    );
}
```

### 3. Dynamic Task Management

If you are using custom task structures, the way tasks are spawned also varies. For instance, you can use `oneapi::tbb::task_group` in oneTBB, which supports deferred execution of tasks:

**Legacy TBB Example:**

```cpp
root.set_ref_count(3);
tbb::task::spawn(child1);
```

**Migrated to oneTBB:**

```cpp
oneapi::tbb::task_group tg;
tg.run([]{ /* Child task logic */ });
tg.wait(); // Wait for all tasks to finish
```

### 4. Managing Thread Concurrency

In oneTBB, concurrency management is more explicit. Instead of relying on implicit configurations, you can set specific thread limits:

```cpp
#include <oneapi/tbb/global_control.h>

// Globally limit thread count
oneapi::tbb::global_control limit(oneapi::tbb::global_control::max_allowed_parallelism, 2);
```

### 5. Finalizing Tasks

Finally, if you need to ensure that all tasks finish before your application exits, you should use `oneapi::tbb::finalize()` method:

```cpp
#include <oneapi/tbb/task_scheduler_handle.h>

int main() {
    oneapi::tbb::task_scheduler_handle handle{tbb::attach{}};
    // Run your parallel work
    oneapi::tbb::parallel_for(/* Parallel code */);
    oneapi::tbb::finalize(handle); // Ensure completion
}
```

### Summary
These changes require significant adjustments to how tasks and concurrency are managed in your application, so thorough testing during the migration process is recommended. Check the provided documentation for deeper insights into each aspect of the migration.

